<br>
Looking around she saw Jerron, sprawled out on the floor. It was very seldom he'd pick up a drink, but last night he gave in. For the past month, 3 of their friends had been missing, and the loss of their presence was beginning to take its toll. <br>
<br>
Sighing, Carmen let her sleek blonde hair fall around her shoulders and down to her mid-back. She took the band that had been holding it away from her face and put it around her wrist. <br>
<br>
Carmen pulled her knees to her chest, hugging them to herself tightly. Laying her forehead on her knees, a single tear rolled down her cheek. She missed Jash. Derek. Mika. They were all special to her. Even if she hadn't known them very long...<br>
<br>
Turning her head slightly, she looked over to Nefer. She was curled up in the recliner, a beer barely being held by her frail hand. Nefer was really taking the most emotional beating. She hardly ate, always slept. Jerron and Carmen both tried their hardest to get her to let go a little, but they were even taking a massive beating. <br>
<br>
Closing her eyes, Carmen thought about Devin. He left early that morning to meet up with his girlfriend, Kali, that was her name. She hardly came around the apartment anymore, bad karma or something. Carmen supposed she was waiting until things settled down. <br>
<br>
Tears were beginning to accumulate at the corners of her eyes, she wasn't about to cry though. She swung her feet off the couch, and forced herself to stand. She had gotten used to running around the apartment in just a tank-top and her underwear. Jerron didn't seem to care, and Nefer was a girl too. She understood what it mean't to just let go at home. <br>
<br>
Stepping over Jerron she grabbed a blanket and took it over to Nefer, and put it over her. She removed the beer bottle from her hand, then pushed a piece of her light chesnut hair away from her eyes. The last month had brung Nefer and Carmen close. Especially, once Carmen's father kicked her out, said since she's never home anyways she might as well not live there. Sorry, she was busy tending to her friends, to herself. <br>
<br>
After going to the kitchen to throw out the bottle, she walked back to the living room and laid a blanket over Jerron. Kneeling beside him, she ran a finger over the side of his face, quietly she spoke, &quot;They're alright...&quot; Carmen said to him, but mainly to herself. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;font-family:verdana;font-size:small;">&quot;Beware the storm, it holds a stength beyond the imagination.&quot;</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/bfantasystoriesforum.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bellonakali>Bellona Kali</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://auction.2y.net/user/kanachan/jsk2.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Child of Hate</span><br>  Posts: 664<br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/19/02 2:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ffantasystoriesforumfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://auction.2y.net/user/kanachan/XMas_1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: S'Just Life</span><hr size=1> Nefertiti russled in her sleep. 6:55 am. Progressivly over the minutes the russling became more of a struggle against unseen demons in her dreams. 6:59. One minute away, but would today be any acception? <br>
<br>
&quot;NOOO!&quot; <br>
<br>
Nope. 7:00 am, right on cue. Throwing herself back just seconds before her mind was shocked back into reality she caused the chair she slept in to topple over and herself to roll out. <br>
<br>
&quot;Nefer!&quot; Just like every morning for forever it seemed, Carmen was at her side, brushing her hair from her forehead with eyes tainted in worry. Sleeping in usually wasn't an option around the small Nefertiti, at least not at 7:00 am. At the same time she woke up, almost always screaming or flailing about. It scared her friends, only because she wouldn't talk about it. Not that she talked much in the first place, except to Carmen. It was the sheer fact that they had no idea what plagued her dreams and tormented her sleep in such a way that it would knock her from her chair screaming at a volume that made their stomachs tighten with fear and their heads swim with worry. She wasn't hurt, rattled, but not hurt. Thinning arms clung tightly around Carmen, this morning was the worst yet. Nefertiti's eyes had all but lost the tiny glimmer they once held, and now she looked like a shadow of her former self. It was nearly impossible to get her to smile, she was withdrawn and never left the house without one of her friends, but her weight was probably the thing that changed the most. Before she had at least some muscle, but now she was all skin an bones. Barely weighing in at 96 pounds her friends began to worry if a docter should be called. Then again, 95 was an improvement from two months ago when it was only 87. They thought they were going to lose her for a little while there. Hopefully her eating habits would continue to improve at the rate they were, then maybe she'd be eating normally again by the end of the year, which was just around the bend. <br>
<br>
Nefertiti felt a hand run through her hair comfortingly and her grip loosened. By not Carmen knew exacatally how to calm her without words. They both knew that nothing could be said to help the painful situation they were in. Sighing heavily, Nefer rested her head on Carmen's chest. The beat of her heart ringing in her ear helped her relax and forget about the dream. Today would be a better day. She could feel it in her bones. She might eat something for breakfast, she felt a little hungery, and then maybe head out to the gym with one of the group- she missed being physically strong. She remembered when Derek used to take her to the gym to lift weights, he said every girl should be strong enough to take care of herself cuz bein pretty didn't get ya everything. She missed him. And she missed the others, espeshally Mika. Nefertiti had taken the loss of her three friends as if the entire group had died and left her alone and sometimes she felt that way and often thought that way. Tears would have been running down her cheeks by now, but they wouldn't. She couldn't even cry anymore. Hugging Carmen tighter, she burried her face in her shoulder. At least, she thought, with every tear I don't shed, I become that much stronger. Once you're at the bottom, there's no where else to go but up.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Right?...<br>
<br>
