<br>
Out of the corner of her eye, Carmen saw Jerron make a run for the bathroom. 'Must be a hang over,' Carmen thought. She'd leave him be... Seconds ticked, by followed by minutes. Soon the half-hour mark... Then 6:44 rolled around. <br>
<br>
Carmen decided to go check on Jerron who was still in the bathroom. Rapping on the door lightly, she called, &quot;Jerron, Hon? You alright?&quot; When he didn't answer she was near panic. Opening the door she saw him huddled over the toilet. Putting a hand on her chest she, kneeled beside him and flushed the toilet.<br>
<br>
Placing a tender hand on his back she rubbed it, there was no need for words. Carmen just wanted to comfort him, by his grave looks she decided to keep quiet for now.<br>
<br>
Time ticked on, and Carmen sat with Jerron, but then... that thud rang through the apartment. Pushing herself onto her feet, Carmen bolted out of the bathroom.<br>
<br>
As she ran back into the living room, the drenched rats' nest that made her hair flung water every where. The accumulated water on her body, soaked her clothes, but it was better than being naked, no need to scare Jerron that early in the morning.<br>
<br>
&quot;Nefer!&quot; Carmen cried as she slid a foot across the carpet towards her petrified friend. Carmen's arms encircled Nefer, holding her close. Brushing Nefer's chesnut hair away from her face, she sighed. Her stomach was in complete knots of worry as she wiped the tears from her frail friend's cheeks. &quot;Nefer... Shhh... Sugar... It's alright,&quot; Carmen said quietly next to her ear. <br>
<br>
As Neferiti cried in her arms, Carmen stroked her hair, and let her release the tension that was building inside of her. Glancing at the clock on the antique DVD player, Carmen sighed. It was 7:02 in the morning. It seemed like this happened every morning, at the same time. No, that was a lie. It DID happen every morning at the same time, and every morning the episode grew worse. Every morning Carmen felt a new pang of fear, a new knot of worry. <br>
<br>
Nefer's skeletal frame began to loosen its grip on Carmen, the chaos was almost over for the morning. Leaning her head against Nefer's, Carmen looked up to see Jerron, moving the chair back into its correct position. He'd been too distraught to use the force of his mental capabilities anymore. It worried Carmen, grandly, but he was getting used to old-fashioned ways of living. <br>
<br>
Carmen rubbed Neferiti's back, then quietly started, &quot;Nefer, why don't you go take a shower? Jerron and I'll worry about breakfast. You need to eat something.&quot; Glancing up to Jerron, she hoped he got teh message he needed to, too.<br>
<br>
Feeling Nefer's head move up and down against her shoulder, Carmen let her go. Watching her head down the hall, she sighed, then she realized Neferiti hadn't cried. Only at first out of fear, but then... she was just... paralyzed in a way. Looking up to Jerron, Carmen's violet eyes glazed over a little, then she shook her head brushing away the sadness. She needed to be strong for Nefer, for Jerron, for herself. Neferiti was alright for now, but Carmen had a breakfast to fix...<br>
<br>
